                            <h2>Initial Thoughts</h2>
                            <p>
                                I went in to this project with a fairly strong stance that schooling should be mandatory, and that mandatory military service was a violation of human rights. While I still stand fairly firmly on those topics, reading conflicting articles and actively trying to provide alternative viewpoints to 
                                those articles has provided me with useful insight in to why some people would think differently than how I do. Enough insight, in fact, that I have changed some of my views to be more considerate of alternate perspectives.
                            </p>
                            <h2>Closing Arguments</h2>
                            <p>
                                As with all opinions, the one I have chosen is based completely on perspective, with no one answer being the "correct" one. That being said, I think I have made several valid points both for compulsory education, and against mandatory military service. If you still believe that making children recieve
                                and education is a violation of human rights, then there is nothing left I can say that may change that. If you are still convinced that we need to force people between the ages of 21 and 23 to serve in the military, then power to you to argue that point. Opposing political viewpoints are not something that should 
                                be discouraged, but rather something that should be celebrated and discussed. Without opposing viewpoints, we would never have unexpected successes when trying new things, because there would be nothing to make us try something new. There comes a point where viewpoints go from reasonable to extreme, but as long as 
                                we can stay away from that line, our society will thrive regardless of who or what is in power. 
                            </p>
