                                <div class = "backTitle">A practical argument for ending compulsory education.</div>
                                <div class = "backBody">
                                    <div class = "backSourceName">Article written by Aaron Osmond</div>
                                    <div class="backBodyText">
                                        <h2>The Suggestion</h2>
                                        <p>
                                            The premise of this article is that children learn better when taught by a direct relative versus when they're taught by someone they have no emotional connection to<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[1]</sup></span>. It also states that, by letting someone else take control of your children's learning, you can disengage from their life comletely.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[1]</sup></span> 
                                            While this is a valid point, I think it ignores the fact that many parents can't afford to spend a large portion of their week teaching someone else without pay. Many parents, for instance, are single and / or poor who need the income that they acquire during the time that would be spent teaching. The second main point the article makes is that we need to change the 
                                            public mindset on education being the most important thing for children to complete. Instead of focusing on education, it says, we should focus on growth and development.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[1]</sup></span> While this is all well and good, it ignores the fact that an educated society is surperior in every way to an uneducated one by both social standards and
                                            physical standards. <span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[9]</sup></span>
                                        </p>
                                        <h2>A Compromise</h2>
                                        <p>
                                            I think a fair compromise would be a government program that provided a small income to parents based on the amount of time per week they spend teaching their children. There are quite a few issues with this, but it seems like the best compromise of the matter for the suggested argument. It could possibly be abused by claiming that you spent time teaching when in 
                                            reality you didn't, but this could be accounted for by strict schedule checking and routine audits. To be frank, though, I don't think this would be a good idea. Many people simply are not fit to be teachers, and this would be reflected in the quality of education the children got. Aditionally, matching the teaching schedule of the children between the parents and the school
                                            teachers would be quite a task.
                                        </p>
