                                <div class="backTitle">Why is school compulsory?</div>
                                <div class = "backBody">
                                    <div class = "backSourceName">Article written by Kevin Currie-Knight</div>
                                    <div class="backBodyText">
                                        <h2>The Article</h2>
                                        <p>
                                                This article looks at the cultural aspects of schooling, rather than the physical aspects. In a society where the most asked question to young children is “What did you do in school today?”<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[5]</sup></span>, and the first part of a resume that an employer looks at is the education section, phasing out
                                                 mandatory schooling for all would be quite difficult.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[3]</sup></span> This portion I wholeheartedly agree with in terms of a statement, but I don’t think the idea that “We did it this way before, so we should continue doing it this way” is a good way to look at an issue. Rather, we should look at why
                                                  we did it that way before, and see if those terms still apply to today’s society. 
                                        </p>
                                        <h2>Why we did it before</h2>
                                        <p>
                                                The first law requiring children to go to school was passed in Massachusetts in 1852.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[4]</sup></span> This law required every town to contain an elementary school that taught basic arithmetic and literacy. Before this point, education was provided by private schools run by churches. After Massachusetts
                                                 precedent, many other states starting following suit. By 1917, every state had laws requiring compulsory education for children.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[4]</sup></span> The main purpose of these laws were to settle the public outcry against child labour. By providing free education, many children could now go to university, 
                                                 and provide themselves with a higher quality of life. States did not enforce compulsory education very strongly until they realized the value of an educated workforce. By this time, education was compulsory up until 12th grade.<span class = "sitedSource"><sup>[4]</sup></span>
                                        </p>
                                        <h2>Do these ideas still apply now?</h2>
                                        <p>
                                                I think the value of having an educated workforce will never not be something a society should strive for. That being said, the fundamental principles on which compulsory education now exists are far different than they were when it was created. For instance, the idea that child labour
                                                 will be exploited is no longer something the population needs to be worried about. Additionally, children now have a better understanding of what they want to do in life, and have access to more resources to find how to achieve that. 
                                        </p>
                                        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
                                        <p>
                                                So, keeping all the above information in mind, I think education should still be compulsory - but to a much more lenient extent. It may seem like the opposite of progress, going back to how something used to be done, but I honestly believe the increase in freedom would benefit a society. We now have access to specific and indepentant methods of learning
                                                through the internet. We no longer need to go to a specific school to become knowledgeable on a subject. 
                                        </p>
